prompt:
This code has a bug. Read the error, identify the problem, and fix it:

```js
const users = [
  { id: 1, name: 'Sarah', plan: 'pro' },
  { id: 2, name: 'Marcus', plan: 'free' }
];

const proUser = users.find(u => u.plan === 'pro');
console.log(`Pro user: ${proUser.name}, ID: ${proUser.id}`);

const freeUser = users.find(u => u.plan === 'team');
console.log(`Team user: ${freeUser.name}`);
// TypeError: Cannot read properties of undefined (reading 'name')
```

Explain: (1) why the error occurs, (2) how to fix it safely.

explanation:
`users.find(u => u.plan === 'team')` returns `undefined` because no user has plan 'team'. Then `undefined.name` throws TypeError.

Fix:
```js
const freeUser = users.find(u => u.plan === 'team');
if (freeUser) {
  console.log(`Team user: ${freeUser.name}`);
} else {
  console.log('No team user found');
}
// Or with optional chaining:
console.log(`Team user: ${freeUser?.name ?? 'not found'}`);
```

Always guard against `.find()` returning `undefined`.

